        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>GBP Insights</strong> (rebranded as <strong>Performance</strong> in Google\u2019s updated interface) is the analytics dashboard that shows how people discover and interact with your Google Business Profile listing. It tracks three areas: <strong>discovery</strong> (search queries and impressions), <strong>location source</strong> (Search vs Maps), and <strong>actions</strong> (website clicks, direction requests, calls, messages).</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Platform</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Google Business Profile</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Data window</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Up to 6 months</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Local SEO teams often optimise a Business Profile and then never look at whether it worked. GBP Insights is the loop. Every category tweak, every new photo, every post can be checked against real query and action data.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is GBP Insights?</h2>
        <p>GBP Insights — now called <strong>Performance</strong> in Google\u2019s updated Business Profile interface — is the analytics dashboard for a Google Business Profile listing. It shows how many people saw the listing, what queries triggered it, whether they viewed on Search or Maps, and which actions they took.</p>
        <p>Historical data is limited to the last six months. Teams that care about year-over-year trends export monthly so the data does not disappear.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why the rename matters</div>
          <p>Google merged the old "Insights" dashboard into a broader "Performance" experience in 2022. The metrics are largely the same but the navigation is different — most public documentation still says "Insights" even though the UI says "Performance". They are the same thing.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why GBP Insights matters</h2>
        <p>Four reasons the Performance dashboard belongs in every monthly local SEO review:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>It reveals the queries you actually rank for.</strong> The query report shows the real search terms customers used — often very different from the ones you optimised for.</li>
          <li><strong>It tracks conversion, not just visibility.</strong> Direction requests and phone calls are proxies for actual visits and inbound leads. Impressions without actions means the listing is visible but not compelling.</li>
          <li><strong>It measures content impact.</strong> Post a new GBP Post or photo, then watch whether views and actions move. Insights is the feedback loop.</li>
          <li><strong>It surfaces seasonality.</strong> Six months of monthly data makes seasonal spikes obvious, so you can front-load content and offers before the surge.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How GBP Insights works</h2>
        <p>The dashboard is organised into three groups: how people find you, where they find you, and what they do after finding you.</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Access the Performance dashboard</span><br>
          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Search your business name while logged in as owner<br>
          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Click <span class="uf-new">Performance</span> in the profile management panel<br>
          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Set date range (max 6 months back)<br>
          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Explore: Overview / Calls / Directions / Website / Queries
        </div>

        <h3>Discovery — how people find you</h3>
        <p>Total searches, impressions by device, and the specific queries that surfaced your listing. Query reports are the highest-signal data in the whole dashboard.</p>

        <h3>Location source — where they find you</h3>
        <p>Split between Google Search and Google Maps. Different behaviour patterns often live on each surface — Maps skews higher-intent, Search skews wider-funnel.</p>

        <h3>Actions — what they do</h3>
        <p>Website clicks, direction requests, phone calls, and messages. These are the closest thing to a conversion metric a local business gets from Google without ecommerce tracking.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Key GBP Insights reports</h2>

