        <h2 id="examples">Real GBP Insights wins</h2>
        <p>Two small businesses that used Insights to change strategy.</p>

        <h3>1. Coffee shop — query report unlocked a fix</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Insights showed 40% of impressions from</span><br>
          <span class="uf-new">"wifi cafe near me"</span><br>
          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Added <span class="uf-new">Free Wi-Fi</span> attribute<br>
          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Updated description to mention Wi-Fi<br>
          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Direction requests up <span class="uf-new">25%</span> in 30 days
        </div>

        <h3>2. HVAC — seasonality spotted early</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Insights showed 300% search spike Jun–Aug</span><br>
          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Published AC blog content in May<br>
          <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> Shifted to heating content in October<br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Content published ahead of demand, not chasing it</span>
        </div>

        <h2 id="vs-related">GBP Insights vs GA4 — which does what</h2>
        <p>Both are analytics tools, both track behaviour, but they measure different surfaces.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>GBP Insights measures</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Your presence on Google Search and Maps</li>
              <li>Queries that triggered your listing</li>
              <li>Actions on the GBP listing itself</li>
              <li>Photo and post engagement</li>
              <li>Direction requests and phone calls</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>GA4 measures</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Behaviour once users reach your website</li>
              <li>All-channel traffic and conversions</li>
              <li>Event-level activity across pages</li>
              <li>Ecommerce transactions and revenue</li>
              <li>Long-term trends beyond 6 months</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for GBP Insights</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Export monthly.</strong> The dashboard only shows six months. Monthly exports preserve year-over-year data that Google will otherwise delete.</li>
          <li><strong>Check the query report first every month.</strong> It is the single most actionable view — your queries change even when your listing does not.</li>
          <li><strong>Watch actions, not impressions.</strong> Impressions without direction requests or calls means the listing appears but does not convert. Fix conversion, not visibility.</li>
          <li><strong>Correlate posts and photos with metric spikes.</strong> Post a GBP Post, add photos, then look at views 7 days later. This is how you learn what your audience wants.</li>
          <li><strong>Track seasonality across a year.</strong> A single monthly view hides seasonal patterns. Six months rolling + monthly exports gives you the full picture.</li>
          <li><strong>Compare Search vs Maps.</strong> If Maps is dominating, your local pack presence is strong. If Search is dominating, you are relying more on organic pack impressions and should audit your website\u2019s local SEO.</li>
          <li><strong>Use direction requests as a heat-map.</strong> They show where your customers actually live — great for choosing where to open next or where to advertise.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — celebrating impressions</div>
          <p>Impressions in GBP Insights are easy to boost with junk visibility (irrelevant queries, low-intent surfaces). Actions — calls, direction requests, website clicks — are the honest metric. A listing whose impressions doubled but whose calls stayed flat is not winning, it is just being seen more.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common GBP Insights mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Never exporting</strong> — the 6-month rolling window will silently delete data you\u2019ll want next year.</li>
          <li><strong>Chasing impressions instead of actions</strong> — impressions without conversions is vanity, not value.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring the query report</strong> — the highest-signal report in the whole dashboard.</li>
          <li><strong>Not connecting posts to metrics</strong> — post something, then check whether it moved views. Otherwise you\u2019re guessing.</li>
          <li><strong>Treating GBP Insights as GA4</strong> — it only measures GBP surfaces. Website behaviour lives in GA4.</li>
          <li><strong>Reading absolute numbers as exact</strong> — trends are reliable, absolutes are estimates.</li>
        </ul>

